Measure of dispersion 

This is measured using following params:

1. Variance
2. Standard Deviation 

Age-1 = {2,2,4,4} Age-2 = {1,1,5,5}
Mean of Age-1 = (2+2+4+4)/4 = 3 
Mean of Age-2 = (1+1+5+5)/4 = 3
Both of them have same mean. But their distribution of data is different, Age-1 has points close to the mean 
Where as Age-2 has points away from the mean 
Spread is less in case of Age-1 and spread is more in case of Age-2

What param can distinguish both age-1 and age-2 spread? Its with variance and Standard Deviation 

 Population Variance:
  σ² = Σ(x - μ)² / N

  Where:
  - σ² (sigma squared) = population variance
  - x = each individual value
  - μ = population mean
  - N = total number of values in the population

  Sample Variance:
  s² = Σ(x - x̄)² / (n - 1)

  Where:
  - s² = sample variance
  - x = each individual value
  - x̄ = sample mean
  - n = sample size
  - (n - 1) = degrees of freedom (Bessel's correction)

  Key difference: Sample variance uses (n-1) instead of n in the denominator to provide an unbiased
  estimate of the population variance.

  For Age-1 the variation is: 1
  For Age-2 variation is : 4 

  So variance is clearly giving that dispersion of the given 
  data is more for Age-2 as we already seen 

  Why Sample variance has divided by (n-1)?

  This correction for sample is called basil correction 

  Usually from sample data we make inference on population data mean, population data variance etc..

  Sample data means we randomly select some data from population
  
  case-1: sample mean and variance are nearer to the population mean, then there are no issues, 

  case-2: Where we chosesn sample values such that sample mean is 
  far away from population mean.
  in this scenario if we keep the denominator to (n-1) instead of n 
  then for sample data the variance error can be reduced from the 
  population variance. That means we are not going to under estimate the population variance 
  The modified formulae of variance for sample data is called: 
  Basil correction 